    {
      "text": "Sleep score rebounds night-to-night: a high night is usually followed by a lower one (rho=-0.27, p=0.021, n=75). After a top-third sleep score night it averages 66.6 vs 74.8 after a bottom-third night. Classic sleep homeostasis \u2014 your body corrects toward balance.",
      "impact": "neutral"
    },
    {
      "text": "REM sleep shows a suggestive rebound: 66.5min after a high night vs 85.8min after a low one (p=0.074, n=25+25).",
      "impact": "neutral"
    },
    {
      "text": "Total sleep shows a suggestive rebound: 5.9h after a high night vs 6.7h after a low one (p=0.088, n=25+25).",
      "impact": "neutral"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deep sleep is the steady exception \u2014 it neither carries over nor rebounds (rho=+0.02, n.s.), holding roughly constant regardless of the night before. Your body defends it.",
      "impact": "positive"
    },
    {
      "text": "Across-metric carryover is weak: the strongest is more deep sleep \u2192 less light sleep next night (rho=-0.29, p=0.013), but none of the 42 cross-metric links survive multiple-comparison correction. Each night mostly stands alone.",
      "impact": "neutral"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bedtime timing shows no clear next-night effect \u2014 late vs early nights land within a few points of each other on every sleep metric (all p>0.1).",
      "impact": "neutral"
    }
  ]
